## AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

**Blog Gen Instruction:** This section is your primary creative brief. Use this audience data to inform every paragraph, every sentence, every word choice. You are writing for a redhead who has strong identity around their hair colour and wants nail inspo that feels made for them. Satisfy them completely.

### Intent-Specific Audience Profile

**Who they are:** Women 18–40 with natural or dyed red hair (ginger, copper, auburn, strawberry blonde, deep red), predominantly fair-skinned with cool-to-neutral undertones, often freckled. Strong identity community — self-identify as "redheads" or "gingers," follow redhead-specific accounts, actively seek content made for them rather than adapted from generic guides. Both at-home manicure fans and salon-goers. US, UK, Canada, Australia primary markets.

**What they want from this post:** Visual inspiration and a confident shortlist of shades they know will work — not another list of shades that "might" look nice, but shades with editorial conviction backed by reasoning they can trust. They want to feel seen as redheads, not lumped into a generic "fair skin" category.

**What satisfies them:** Specific shade names they can screenshot and take to a salon or buy directly. A clear explanation of WHY a color works (not just "it looks great") that respects their intelligence. Acknowledgment of the different "types" of redhead — they know strawberry blondes and auburn are different. The occasional myth-busting moment (yes, you can wear red / orange / neon — here's how).

**What frustrates them:** Generic "fair skin" advice that treats all pale people the same. Seasonal content that only gives them 7 shades for spring and then they have to find a different article for summer. The vague warning "avoid clashing with your hair" without any useful guidance on what that actually means. Content that only shows one "type" of redhead (usually very fair copper/ginger) while ignoring auburn, strawberry, and darker reds.

### Top 5 Pain Points (Intent-Filtered)

1. Not knowing if a shade will actually "go" with their specific shade of red hair — they've been burned by shades that looked stunning in a swatch but wrong against their hair
2. Feeling excluded from general nail colour guides that address skin tone but never hair colour as a variable
3. Confusion around "rules" — can they wear red? Orange? Neon? The internet gives contradictory answers
4. Finding nudes that don't make their hands look washed out or "mannequin-like" — this is a recurring specific complaint in forum communities
5. Needing a seasonless resource that works year-round, not having to hunt for seasonal posts every three months

